<p>Hello again. This is Roger Coke Barr for the bioelectricity course and we're starting week 5 of our course. Thank you for being here. We have an exciting but different topic today. We're going to talk this week about currents in the structure. By analogy, we are talking about the track on which the train runs. Please keep in mind, as you think about this topic, that this is one of the three topics, three, four, five, one of the three topics that could be taken in any order. So, topic number five is independent of topics three and topic four. So talking about the track is really fundamentally different. As compared to what we have done up until this time. We are now for the first time not staying in place in one little patch on the membrane, but rather examining what happens as currents flow from one place to another. There are two aspects of this for which we need quantitative results. The first, which I've called axial currents inside and outside. Are the currents that flow from one place to another, either in the space inside the cells or in the space outside the cells. The second is a consequence of the first,at some point along the fiber, the fact the current stopped flowing inside forces them outside. At other points along the fiber or in a group of cells the fact the currents start flowing inside means the current has to come through the membrane from the outside. So we want to know what about these membrane currents that are forced to be present. By the need to supply, or to get rid of,the axial currents. These are our two major topics for the week. So, we have two groups of topics that I’ve divided as usual. In the first, this, the first, we’ll emphasize that this week is a little different from what we have done so far. And in particular, we will have to get straight a bunch of little things. All these are just little things that we have to get straight in order to deal with the track, rather than with the train. Where the ball electricity sense, there a