the current is in the patch must stay in the patch or in other words, IM is equal to zero. There is a little bit of exception there where we have introduced a stimulus current for a short while. But this really had nothing to do with the neighbors. You will find that when there are lots of patches, and there always are lots of patches in naturally occurring tissue. One patch has a strong effect on what happens in the next patch, and that patch on the ones beside it. So, there is a chain reaction type of operation. Each one has an effect on the others. And, mathematically, this effect of each patch on the next is expressed by changes in the value of the membrane current, IM..There's another thing. Up until now, we've talked about patches in isolation, with very little need to talk about the specific structure from which they came. We’ve mentioned along the way, frog muscle, squid axon but by and large, we’ve talked about patches all alone in the world. Well, it's just not like that anymore. Things are different now. We’re examining how one patch interacts with its neighbors. And to do that, we have to do that for a particular tissue structure. So in this segment with this picture of some dead campus flowers. As you know flower bushes one flower has an affect on the others, these travel from place to place the whole entire process in nature depends not just on individual flowers as important as they are, but on their interactions and their interactions with their surroundings so there can be flowers this year, next year and the year after. Let's see just how this works in the subsequent segments.</p>

